Subject: RE: [T2] AVP Engine Swap Experience (long) Part 1.

On Wed, 27 Mar 2002, Mark Durrant wrote:

a bus with an automatic tranny does not need to be pulled anywhere near as
far back and can easily be removed with the tranny still installed.  so
this information on engine removal should be noted to only be required for
manual tranny buses

Bob


> Well, I am glad that I am not the only one that didn't know this. Lou (my mechanic) was pretty harsh on me about this one "everyone knows that...", etc.
> 
> I think you are supposed to support the rear (bell housing side) of the trans with a jack during engine removal, then use a coathangar or something to support it once you have the engine out and the jack out. The idea is that by dropping the trans a few inches, the engine can kind of slide out at an angle. 
> 
> I didn't do this, and I found that the muffler and top of the fan housing wanted to hit the body of the bus before the bottom studs were clear of the transmission. I guess if you removed the muffler and maybe the fan housing first then it would clear OK. It was only with a lot of wiggling and slightly damaging one of the trans holes that I got it out. The process did not look very professional. Maybe there is more than one way to do this correctly?
> 
> Mark
> '78 'blue bus'
> 
> 
> >> needed to be. I did learn a few useful things: There are 6
> >> bolts (not 4) at the front of the engine that need to be
> >> removed. The four that hold the engine to the trans everyone
> >> knows about. However to properly remove the engine, you must
> >> also remove two bolts on top of the trans that hold the trans
> >> to the frame. The idea is that you are supposed to put a jack
> >> under the trans and lower it a few inches, which will allow
> >> everything to be removed smoothly. I removed my engine
> >> without doing this which is not supposed to be possible.
> >> That's part of why the engine removal was such a bear.
> >
> >Hmm, I'm not sure if I understand.  I've only removed mine (a '79)
> >once, but I just removed the 4 bolts (and the engine bearer) and it
> >came right out, and I did read the manual.
> >
> >If you removed the tranny mounts, how did you secure the tranny when
> >the engine was out?  Ooh, that just reminded me of a question for the
> >list that I'll post later ...
